title: IntentText — Claims Verification Checklist
summary: Every trust claim .it makes, and how to prove each is TRUE. Run verify-claims.mjs for the automated pass.

meta: | type: checklist | owner: QA | scope: trust

info: This file is itself a .it document — it dogfoods the format. The runnable companion is verify-claims.mjs (27 assertions); the property-based gate is packages/core/tests/byte-preservation.test.ts (thousands of random docs). | type: tip

section: 1. Integrity — the seal is tamper-evident, offline
task: Sealing a document returns a sha256: hash | owner: core | check: sealDocument().hash
task: A sealed document verifies intact | owner: core | check: verifyDocument(sealed).intact === true
task: A one-byte edit to the body makes verify FAIL | owner: core | check: verifyDocument(tampered).intact === false
done: The seal is computed over raw source bytes, so it is safe at rest

section: 2. Byte preservation — the bytes are sacred
task: Round-trip is byte-for-byte | owner: core | check: documentToSource(parseIntentText(src)) === src
task: A no-op edit keeps the seal | owner: editor | check: reconcileEdit(sealed, sealed) === sealed
task: An editor round-trip preserves the seal | owner: editor | check: reconcileEdit restores bytes, verify intact
task: Property order is preserved (no canonical reorder) | owner: core | check: byte-preservation.test.ts I1
task: Editing one block leaves every other block's bytes intact | owner: core | check: byte-preservation.test.ts I5

section: 3. Storage — re-encoding is detected, not absorbed
task: A clean storage round-trip verifies | owner: core | check: verifyStorageRecord(record) === true
task: A storage layer that rewrites LF to CRLF is caught | owner: core | check: verifyStorageRecord(mutated) === false

section: 4. Authenticity — identity needs an anchor (be honest)
task: An Ed25519 signature verifies valid | owner: sign | check: verifyCryptoSignatures(signed) all valid
task: Tampering invalidates the signature | owner: sign | check: verifyCryptoSignatures(tampered) not valid
task: A plain sign: with no key is a named approval, not crypto | owner: sign | check: cryptographic !== true
info: Binding a key to a real legal identity needs the certify: chain (Layer 3) or your app's identity registry. | type: warning

section: 5. Workflow — state is derived, never stored
task: With approvals outstanding the workflow is not complete | owner: core | check: workflowState().complete === false
task: Sequential next points at the first required approver | owner: core | check: workflowState().next
task: Conditional require: (when:) activates on the document's own values | owner: core | check: active includes finance
task: After all required approve, the workflow is complete | owner: core | check: workflowState().complete === true

section: 6. Audit — the approval ORDER is tamper-evident
task: A chained approval trail verifies valid | owner: core | check: verifyAuditChain(src).valid === true
task: Reordering approvals breaks the chain | owner: core | check: verifyAuditChain(reordered).brokenAt is set

section: 7. Time — native at: is self-asserted (do not overclaim)
task: The native seal carries no RFC-3161 timestamp token | owner: core | check: no tsa token in sealed source
info: Provable time lives on the PAdES PDF export (@dotit/pades requestTimestampToken), not the native .it. | type: warning

section: How to run
text: From the repo root, after building the packages with `pnpm -r build`.
text: Run the automated claim checks (27 assertions): `node verify/verify-claims.mjs`
text: Run the property-based byte-preservation gate (thousands of random docs): `cd packages/core && npx vitest run tests/byte-preservation.test.ts`
done: This file is a .it document — it round-trips byte-for-byte through the core
